LINKEDLIST 

---

1. WHAT IS LINKEDLIST

---

* Collection of nodes
* Each node contains:

  1. Data
  2. Reference (next pointer)

---

2. TYPES OF LINKEDLIST

---

* Singly LinkedList
* Doubly LinkedList
* Circular LinkedList

---

3. NODE STRUCTURE

---

class Node {
int data;
Node next;
}

---

4. HOW IT WORKS

---

* Elements are NOT stored in contiguous memory
* Each node points to the next node
* Last node points to null

---

5. HEAD

---

* First node of the list
* Entry point to access LinkedList

---

6. TIME COMPLEXITY

---

* Insert at head → O(1)
* Insert at tail → O(n)
* Search → O(n)
* Delete → O(n)

---

7. ADVANTAGES

---

* Dynamic size
* Efficient insertion and deletion
* No need for resizing

---

8. DISADVANTAGES

---

* No direct access (no index)
* Extra memory required for pointers
* Traversal required for most operations

---

9. ARRAY VS LINKEDLIST

---

ARRAY:

* Contiguous memory
* Fast access → O(1)
* Fixed size

LINKEDLIST:

* Non-contiguous memory
* Access time → O(n)
* Dynamic size

---

10. KEY INTERVIEW POINT

---

"LinkedList stores elements as nodes where each node points to the next node, allowing dynamic memory usage but slower access compared to arrays."

  
LINKEDLIST CODING PROGRAMS:

---

1. CREATE LINKEDLIST + INSERT AT END

---

class LinkedListDemo {

```
static class Node {
    int data;
    Node next;

    Node(int data) {
        this.data = data;
        this.next = null;
    }
}

Node head;

public void insert(int data) {
    Node newNode = new Node(data);

    if (head == null) {
        head = newNode;
        return;
    }

    Node temp = head;
    while (temp.next != null) {
        temp = temp.next;
    }

    temp.next = newNode;
}

public void print() {
    Node temp = head;
    while (temp != null) {
        System.out.print(temp.data + " -> ");
        temp = temp.next;
    }
    System.out.println("null");
}
```

}

---

2. INSERT AT BEGINNING

---

public void insertAtHead(int data) {
Node newNode = new Node(data);
newNode.next = head;
head = newNode;
}

---

3. DELETE NODE BY VALUE

---

public void delete(int key) {
if (head == null) return;

```
if (head.data == key) {
    head = head.next;
    return;
}

Node temp = head;

while (temp.next != null && temp.next.data != key) {
    temp = temp.next;
}

if (temp.next != null) {
    temp.next = temp.next.next;
}
```

}

---

4. REVERSE LINKEDLIST

---

public void reverse() {
Node prev = null;
Node curr = head;
Node next;

```
while (curr != null) {
    next = curr.next;
    curr.next = prev;
    prev = curr;
    curr = next;
}

head = prev;
```

}

---

5. FIND MIDDLE NODE

---

public void findMiddle() {
Node slow = head;
Node fast = head;

```
while (fast != null && fast.next != null) {
    slow = slow.next;
    fast = fast.next.next;
}

System.out.println("Middle: " + slow.data);
```

}

---

6. DETECT CYCLE

---

public boolean hasCycle() {
Node slow = head;
Node fast = head;

```
while (fast != null && fast.next != null) {
    slow = slow.next;
    fast = fast.next.next;

    if (slow == fast) {
        return true;
    }
}

return false;
```

}

